Dance performances; culmination of
Laboratory Project
Wind Shear (plates 86, 87) was a collaborative dance piece
created by choreographer Meg Eginton and visual artist
Al Taylor, with live music composed and played by Pat
Irwin. The creative exchange between Taylor and Eginton
centered on aesthetic concerns and an interest in the for-
mal investigations of movement rather than abstract or
conceptual ideas.' Taylor conceived a set of tubular white
forms, which could be moved throughout the space,
in direct dialogue with Eginton's choreography. These
sculptures were suspended at different heights, some
midair and others just above the ground, as if they had
paused mid-fall. Their lines resembled those of the ara-
besques and staccato movements of the dancers, who
included Eginton as well as Patricia Chen, Hilary Harper,
and Denise Mostacci, all dressed in jewel-toned leotards.
The creation of Wind Shear spanned ten weeks, from
conceptualization and exploration to rehearsals and pro-
duction. It was the first work developed entirely in the
context of the Laboratory Program, which was, as the
press release explained, "designed to encourage exper-
imentation in the arts through the provision of facilities
for research and development from conceptualization to
project realization and possible public presentation." In
developing the Laboratory Program, and the Corporation
for Art and Television (CAT) to which it belonged (see
Chronology, p. 151), the JAM team was responding to the
information it had gathered in informal conversations with
artists and art workers, who reported that the rising costs

development and experimentation" difficult to sustain,
as organizations and artists were forced to prioritize work
that responded to the commercial market."
This challenge was particularly acute for dancers and
other performance-based artists whose work depended
on access to rehearsal space. In 1985, several dance and
performance artists benefited from the availability of
JAM's space, through the CAT Laboratory and other pro-
grams. Among them were the postmodern dancer and
choreographer Yoshiko Chuma and her performance-art
group the School of Hard Knocks; Jane Comfort, who
performed TV Love, a blend of dance and theater staged
against a backdrop of colorful gridded words; and the
Indigenous ensemble Spiderwoman Theater.
Although the CAT Laboratory Program marked a
significant shift of emphasis toward performance and
dance, JAM had already begun to establish itself as a
space for innovative movement practice in the years
prior. In 1983, Tony Whitfield curated the performance
series American Dreams, which featured several solo
works, including a one-night presentation of Adrienne.
Altenhaus's Oral Satisfaction, the fourth part of her ongo-
ing performance Stress Test, which examined Americans'
relationships to health, and Jeff McMahon's Believe You
Me, an investigation-by way of dance, video, text,
music, and images-of "Home, the road there, and what
waits for you upon arrival." -YK

"Rock 'n' Roll is Black music and we are its heirs," pro-
claimed the Black Rock Coalition," which was formed
in the fall of 1985 by musicians, writers, and artists who
were frustrated with the music industry's resistance
to Black people playing rock music. A weekly meeting
was held at Just Above Midtown, headed by JAM friends
including Vernon Reid, Craig Street, and Greg Tate."2
Among the other core members were Geri Allen, Melvin
Gibbs, and Bruce Mack, who would later form the band
Burnt Sugar the Arkestra Chamber with Tate. The group
quickly moved from thoughtful and constructive dis-
cussions about the state of the music industry to cre-
ating their own programming geared toward musicians
who occupied the fringes. At a moment when, as Tate
put it, "Black people were just getting picked up to be in
rhythm sections for people like David Bowie," the Black
Rock Coalition stood critical of the white rock industry
and supportive of "those who rock black." The organi-
zation continues its vital work today. -MI

B Culture: "Sushi and the Crips"

"There is no such thing as white ink" read the tagline of B
Culture (1986-87), which was conceived and edited by
musician and music critic Greg Tate and music producer
Craig Dennis Street, and provided a platform for Black
creators working across various mediums and styles.
The first issue, "Sushi and the Crips," takes readers from
Arthur Jafa's notes on Black cinema to graffiti artists' dis-
cussions of their craft to an interview with saxophonist
Wayne Shorter to a short story by Ntozake Shange. The
second, "Voodoo Against Racism," includes an inter-
view with Miles Davis, a centerfold photograph by Lorna
Simpson, and a provocative yet playful critique of Andy
Warhol by Tate. The third and final issue, "Glossalaila,"
opens with a neo-noir comic strip about an antihero.
B Culture was the second of two artists' quarterlies
JAM produced during its decade-long run, both of which
attempted to expand what the form could offer artists
and writers. The first was the four-issue Black Currant
(1982-83), conceived and edited by artist Janet Olivia
Henry. In it, Henry featured original artist projects that
pushed the boundaries of three basic formal and con-
ceptual elements of publications: space, authorship,
and language. In vol. 2 no. 1, the space between pages
acts as a third dimension and the fulcrum for narrative
coherence. Each of the dozen contributing artists was
given a square on each of the ten pages for an image
of their making. As the reader flips through the issue,
they can either understand the images-which include
photographic portraits, text images, figure drawings,
and abstract designs-in relation to their counterparts
on the same page or follow each artist's contributions
